<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 07-47-03R - Excessive Heat in Driver's Compartment</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi074703" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>07-47-03R</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>July 2007</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>Bus Body</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Excessive Heat in Driver's Compartment</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <distribution dealer="yes" fleet="yes" bodybuilder="no" isis_cd="yes"/>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>FE Bus
                    <daterange>
                        <startdate>01/01/2005</startdate>
                        <enddate>03/31/2007</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">REVISION DESCRIPTION</emph>
                </para>
                <para>The build end date changed to 03/31/2007.</para>
                <para>This procedure addresses complaints of excessive heat in the driver's compartment and at the
                    entrance door step well.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
        <partsinfo>
            <para>Kit Number: 2594666C91 &#8722; Field installed dash insulator kit</para>
        </partsinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="29">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or death, shift transmission to neutral or park, set parking brake,
                        and block wheels before doing diagnostic or service procedures.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f07470301" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470301.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1.</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Tools required: Drill, .140" dia. bit, .150" dia. bit, #2 Phillips bit, 5/16" socket and ratchet, flat
                blade screw driver, awl, 4" putty knife, cup to hold removed fasteners, flash light or shop light.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Keep all parts for re-installation.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Verify that the bus has engine cover seals and driver's rubber foot pad (see lower
                    portion of Figure 2). If the bus does not have driver's rubber foot pad, then order kit #2588896c92
                    and install prior to kit 2594666c91 - Field installed dash insulator kit.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The VIN Build date range for kit 2588896c92 is 01-01-2005 to 10-18-2005.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f07470312" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470312.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="328px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To Remove Plastic Instrument Cluster / LH Dash Cover and HVAC Controls</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Unscrew all 4 mounting screws around the driver's side (HVAC) control assembly (see
                        Figure 3 and 4).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470302" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470302.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470303" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470303.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove gray screw covers and screws from the instrument cluster / LH dash cover.
                        (See Figure 5 and 6).
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Do not remove the fasteners circled. Removal of fasteners could separate wires (see
                                Figure 6). The LH Dash will flex to gain access (see Figure 9).
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="f07470304" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470304.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470305" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470305.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove driver's side filler panel (see Figure 7 and 8). This will give access for
                        mechanic's fingers to get underneath and pull forward to separate the instrument cluster from
                        the Velcro located underneath.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Loosen the passenger side filler panel.</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="f07470306" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470306.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="312px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470307" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470307.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="312px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 8.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lift the right side of the plastic instrument cluster only 6" to expose the
                        components underneath.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Do not completely remove or lift the entire instrument cluster (see Figure 9).</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="f07470308" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470308.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 9.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To Remove Top Plastic Dash Fascia / RH Dash Cover</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">There may be a need to remove auxiliary equipment such as: dash mounted video
                        recorder box, dash mounted CB, dash mounted fire extinguisher or others (see Figure 10).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove all gray button screw covers from the top main plastic dash fascia (see
                        Figure 10 and 11).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove all of the top dash mounting screws and screw button shanks.</para>
                    <figure id="f07470309" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470309.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 10.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470310" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470310.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 11.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Seal holes, gaps in metal dash panels.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Prior to sealing, start unit to verify major areas of excessive air flow from the
                        cooling (radiator) fan that escapes into the driver's area via the metal dash panels.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>This may take a long time for the engine to heat up and the fan to turn on, so proceed
                                to the next steps.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Verify that the seal between the engine cover and horse collar is tight and does not
                        allow hot air to blow in while radiator fan is on. If hot air is coming through the seal, adjust
                        the engine cover to the seal to improve fit (see Figure 12).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470311" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470311.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="328px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 12.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Use a very strong flash light or shop light to identify open areas that need to be
                        sealed.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply sealer to all identified open holes and gaps in the horse collar area (metal
                        dash panel that extends from driver's right knee to the right side of the engine cover.)
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Use roll of sealer provided with the kit and follow the red dotted lines in the
                                pictures. Do not use tube caulk. (See Figures 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 and 18.)
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>In Figure 17 and 18 it is only necessary to seal holes that go through both the
                                insulation pad and the sheet metal to the engine compartment.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply sealer to all sides of the shift selector/dash support bracket. Units with a
                        2500 series transmission will have a cable and bracket routed through the horse collar with a
                        boot type seal. Ensure boot seal is in good condition. Units with a 3000 series transmission
                        will have a plate installed under the support bracket (see Figures 13, 14 and 15).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply sealer to the vertical seam of the horse collar extension located behind the
                        HVAC controls and above the engine cover mounting area (see Figure 14).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470313" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470313.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 13.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470314" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470314.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="328px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 14.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470315" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470315.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="328px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 15.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470316" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470316.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="360px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 16.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470317" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470317.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 17.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470318" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470318.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 18.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Inspect area forward of dash and located behind the left windshield wiper access
                        door for open holes. Seal as needed (see Figure 19).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470319" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470319.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 19.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install forward dash insulator pad.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">NOTE: If the engine cover is off for any reason, make sure that the engine
                            cover is re-installed and seated correctly prior to the following steps.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Place dash pad insulator into position against bulkhead (aluminized side to be
                        positioned down facing metal dash panel) and against the driver's right knee panel.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Make sure the top of the pad is positioned so the top edge of pad has enough over lap
                                to be tucked tightly under the plastic dash fascia prior to installing the screws at the
                                HVAC controls (see Figure 20, 21 and 22).
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="f07470320" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470320.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 20.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470321" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470321.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 21.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470322" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470322.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 22.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove existing sheet metal screws from the access panels for the step well heater
                        and surge tank area that correspond to the grommet location on the pad (see Figure 23).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Place a black nylon washer on each of the screws. Put screw through grommet in pad
                        and install screw. Follow the procedure until all sheet metal screws have been removed and
                        re-installed.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470323" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470323.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 23.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">No washers will be used on the 4 mounting screws around the driver's side HVAC
                        control assembly (see Figure 24).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using a punch (awl) or similar sharp pointed object, locate the four holes behind
                        the HVAC control assembly, re-attach HVAC control assembly over the top of the dash insulator
                        pad and tighten screws (sheet metal screws will pass easily through the insulator pad - see
                        Figure 24).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470324" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470324.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 24.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">CAUTION - Only drill holes specified by grommet locations on the passenger
                            side. Drilling holes in any other location may result in puncturing coolant or stepwell
                            heater components. Use drill a limiter sleeve or a drill stop that only allows the bit to
                            penetrate 1/4" past the sheet metal.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">For grommet hole locations that do not line up with existing dash hardware, drill a
                        .140" dia pilot hole into the access panels. Place a screw and washer (provided in the kit) into
                        grommet and pilot hole and tighten (see Figure 25).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470325" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470325.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 25.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Wrap pad around driver knee area. Use existing screws and washer to secure pad in
                        place. Drill .140 " dia. hole through the pad and sheet metal in the location shown and secure
                        pad with kit screw and nylon washer.
                        <emph type="bold">CAUTION - Use a limiter sleeve or a drill stop that only allows the bit to
                            penetrate &#188;", because there are wires behind steel (see Figure 26 and 27).
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f07470326" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470326.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 26.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f07470327" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470327.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                                 scalefitheight="352px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 27.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Re-install (all parts) plastic dash fascia, instrument cluster, filler panel, black
                        webbing, screws, screw button covers, video box, and auxiliary equipment.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install floor insulator pad.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">The floor dash insulator pad is to be mounted flush against the engine cover, to the
                        floor, running parallel with the step well edge.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using the existing pilot holes in the ply wood, drill .150" dia. pilot holes into
                        the floor and install insulator pad with 4 black nylon washers and four 1.50" screws.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">NOTE: Some FE buses may have a hand rail that interferes with the pad shown in
                            Figure 28 and 29; therefore the pad will need to be modified.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Un-staple the vinyl cover on one end.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Cut board shorter to fit along step well edge to the hand rail.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Trim vinyl and staple to back side of board.</para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f07470328" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470328.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 28.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f07470329" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G07470329.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 29.</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
    </tsi>
